{{Infobox building | name = Denny Hall | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_size = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = File:Univ of Wash Denny Hall 01.jpg | image_size = | image_alt = <!-- or | alt = --> | image_caption = <!-- or | caption = --> | map_type = | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_size = | map_dot_label = | relief = | former_names = Administration Building | alternate_names = | etymology = | status = | cancelled = | topped_out = | building_type = | architectural_style = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|French Renaissance Revival]] | classification = | location = | address = | location_city = <!-- or | location_town = --> | location_country = | coordinates = | altitude = | current_tenants = | namesake = [[Arthur A. Denny]] | groundbreaking_date = 1894 | start_date = | stop_date = | est_completion = | topped_out_date = | completion_date = | opened_date = 1895 | inauguration_date = | relocated_date = | renovation_date = | closing_date = | demolition_date = <!-- or | destruction_date = --> | cost = | ren_cost = | client = | owner = [[University of Washington]] | landlord = | affiliation = | height = | architectural = | tip = | antenna_spire = | roof = | top_floor = | observatory = | diameter = | circumference = | weight = | other_dimensions = | structural_system = | material = | size = | floor_count = | floor_area = | elevator_count = | grounds_area = | architect = Charles Saunders | architecture_firm = | developer = | engineer = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | other_designers = | quantity_surveyor = | main_contractor = | awards = | designations = | known_for = | ren_architect = | ren_firm = | ren_engineer = | ren_str_engineer = | ren_serv_engineer = | ren_civ_engineer = | ren_oth_designers = | ren_qty_surveyor = | ren_contractor = | ren_awards = | rooms = <!-- or | unit_count = --> | parking = | url = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | embed = | embedded = | references = | footnotes = }}
'''Denny Hall''' is a building on the main campus of the [[University of Washington]], in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], United States. Built between 1894 and 1895, it is named after [[Arthur A. Denny]].
==Design== Denny Hall was designed by Charles Saunders and constructed between 1894 and 1895. The brick and sandstone, French Renaissance Revival building is the oldest on the University of Washington's current campus.{{efn|The University of Washington was founded in 1861 at a different location. It moved from its original [[Downtown Seattle]] site in the [[Metropolitan Tract]] to its current campus in the 1890s.<ref name="pi"/>}} A grassy area planted with large, canopy trees - the Denny Yard - sits in front of the building.<ref>{{cite book|title=Denny Hall Renovation - Draft Site Program Document|date=2007|publisher=[[University of Washington]]|location=[[Seattle, Washington]]|pages=2–4|url=http://opb.washington.edu/sites/default/files/opb/Architecture/ULAC%202007-11-30%20Denny%20Hall%20Site%20Program.pdf|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>
==History== [[File:Administration Building exterior showing north sides of building, University of Washington, Seattle, May 1, 1901 (PEISER 3).jpeg|thumb|Photograph of the Administration Building in 1901]] The cornerstone of the building was laid in a July 1894 ceremony attended by a crowd of about 1,000. Originally called the Administration Building, in 1910 it was renamed after Arthur A. Denny, one of the founders of Seattle and an early benefactor of the university. The building was renovated, first in 1957, and a second time beginning in 2008. The $56&nbsp;million renovation of 2008 was stalled by the [[recession of 2008]] but resumed in 2014 and was completed two years later.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Minnick|first1=Benjamin|title=Denny Hall rehab is back on after being stalled by recession|url=http://www.djc.com/news/co/12066489.html|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=[[Seattle Daily Journal of Commerce]]|date=June 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name="pi">{{cite news|last1=DeMay|first1=Daniel|title=UW's oldest building getting a makeover|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/UW-s-oldest-building-getting-a-makeover-6644111.php|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref><ref name="sdjc">{{cite news|last1=Minnick|first1=Benjamin|title=$56M Denny Hall renovation finishing in August, six months ahead of schedule|url=http://www.djc.com/news/co/12089480.html|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=Seattle Daily Journal of Commerce|date=May 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dorpat|first1=Paul|title=Now & Then — Denny Hall at University of Washington|url=http://www.historylink.org/File/2565|website=[[HistoryLink]]|publisher=HistoryInk|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>
An engraving of Denny Hall is featured on the University of Washington's [[Ceremonial mace|mace]], which is carried and displayed by the Marshal of the University during Convocation and Commencement ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web|title=The University Mace|url=http://www.washington.edu/ceremony/tradition/symbols-meanings/university-mace/|website=Office of Ceremonies|publisher=[[University of Washington]]|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>
Installed in the cupola of Denny Hall is a {{convert|400|lb|adj=on}}, 1859 bell ("the [[Varsity Bell]]") which is rung once per year, on [[Homecoming]], to ceremonially summon the university's alumni to campus. From 1961 until his death in 2013, [[Brewster Denny]] was responsible for the annual ringing of the Varsity Bell.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kelley|first1=Peter|title=Brewster Denny: Five decades ringing in UW Homecoming|url=http://www.washington.edu/news/2011/10/28/brewster-denny-five-decades-ringing-in-uw-homecoming/|accessdate=October 28, 2011|work=UW Today|publisher=[[University of Washington]]|date=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Long|first1=Katherine|title=Denny descendant rings UW's historic bell|url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2016636985_dennybell29m.html|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=[[Seattle Times]]|date=October 28, 2011}}</ref>
As of 2016, the building houses the university's departments of Anthropology, Classics, Germanics and Near Eastern Languages & Civilization.<ref name="sdjc"/>
