[[File:Ballets Russes Apollon 1928.jpg|thumb|''Apollo'' 1928]]
'''Felia Doubrovska''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|Фелия Дубровская (real name Фелицата Леонтьевна Длужневская)}}; born as ''Felizata Dlouzhnevska'' in [[St Petersburg]], February 13, 1896 – d. [[Manhattan]], September 18, 1981) was a [[Russia]]n dancer and teacher.

Doubrovska graduated at the [[Imperial Ballet School]] in 1913, was member of the [[Mariinsky Theatre]] company, and emigrated with her later husband [[Pierre Vladimiroff]] to the West in 1920, where they joined at first the [[Ballets Russes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/pierre-vladimiroff|title=Pierre Vladimiroff|work=Answers.com|accessdate=2016-12-05}}</ref> Amongst others, she danced in the company at New York's [[Metropolitan Opera]] from 1938 to 1939, and taught at [[School of American Ballet]] until the age of 84.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://michaelminn.net/andros/index.php?doubrovska_felia|title=Andros on Ballet - Felia Doubrovska|website=Michaelminn.net|accessdate=2016-12-05}}</ref> She died due to a heart attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/09/21/obituaries/felia-doubrovska-dies-at-85-ballerina-and-noted-teacher.html|title=FELIA DOUBROVSKA DIES AT 85 -  BALLERINA AND NOTED TEACHER - NYTimes.com|date=September 21, 1981|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=2016-12-05}}</ref>

[[Virginia Brooks]], Vice-président Board of Directors of Dance Film Association in USA, created a film ''Felia Doubrovska remembered (Happy to be so...)'', 2008, dedicated to the memory ballerina Felia Doubrovska.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dancefilmsassn.org/DanceOnCamreadeschedule08.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706052627/http://www.dancefilmsassn.org/DanceOnCamreadeschedule08.html |archivedate=July 6, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>

