The '''Performing Arts Training Center''' (PATC) was opened in 1967 in [[East St. Louis, Illinois]] by world-renowned African American dancer [[Katherine Dunham]] who was then Artist-in-Residence at [[Southern Illinois University Edwardsville]]. Dunham partnered with SIUE's Experiment in Higher Education to add educational resources to the program and give the youth of East St. Louis a better educational experience.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siue.edu/graduate/iur/history/dunham-dance.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720011535/http://www.siue.edu/graduate/iur/history/dunham-dance.shtml |archivedate=2014-07-20 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/feature/Giving_Guide_2011/2011/12/southern-illinois-university.html?page=all</ref>
The PATC (later known as the Katherine Dunham Center for the Performing Arts) offered credit and non-credit courses in such arts as dance, martial arts, and crafts. At times, its company of dancers has toured widely. Now known as the Performing Arts Program, it is a part of SIUE's [[Southern Illinois University Edwardsville#East St. Louis Center|East St. Louis Center]],<ref>http://www.siue.edu/news/archives/ArchivesMAR2014.shtml#SIUEEastStLouisCentertoHostBirthdayFestivitiesfortheCity</ref><ref>http://www.stlamerican.com/entertainment/living_it/article_99918fa0-5efe-11e1-9795-0019bb2963f4.html?mode=image&photo=0</ref>
